    "rationale": "This reaction shows the reduction of a simple, acyclic ketone (butan-2-one) to the corresponding alkane (n-butane). This is the quintessential transformation for the Wolff-Kishner reduction, clearly demonstrating the conversion of a carbonyl group (C=O) to a methylene group (CH2) under basic conditions using hydrazine. The reactants and products are small, acyclic, and unambiguous, making it an ideal canonical example.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "This example uses a simple aliphatic ketone to avoid overlap with reactions involving aromatic rings (e.g., Friedel-Crafts acylation/alkylation) or other functional groups. It specifically avoids aldehydes, which could be involved in aldol or Cannizzaro reactions, and avoids cyclic ketones which might be involved in ring expansions (e.g., Tiffeneau-Demjanov) or cleavages. The transformation is a clear deoxygenation of a ketone to an alkane, which is the defining feature of the Wolff-Kishner reduction."
  }
